title: Thought it was great at first...BUT...
text:
Wrote this initial review for the WHITE AND GRAY VERSION: Used to have the Samsung Galaxy S3 and the OtterBox Commuter for that phone and didn't like it as much. It was hard to remove and the buttons were hard to press through the case. I recently switched to the Galaxy S4 and this case and I love it. They made all the right changes to the S3 case to make it perfect. Now it is easy to take on and off of the phone and the buttons are way easier to push through the soft gray part of the case. This one also has a textured hard white cover that has more grip to it than the S3 model. I am very pleased.

After the white and gray version wore out, I purchased the PINK AND GRAY VERSION, WHICH APPEAR TO BE A KNOCK OFF or have some other manufacturing error AND DO NOT FIT THE PHONE CORRECTLY! The cut outs in the pink part of the case do not fit the ports on the phone, which has caused all of the micro-usb metal inserts to be bent on every single one of my charging cords! Finally, one of the prongs on the inside of my phone broke and IT KILLED THE ENTIRE PHONE'S ABILITY TO CHARGE!!! DO NOT BUY THE PINK AND GRAY CASE IT WILL RUIN YOUR PHONE! I was a dedicated Otter Box user before this, but I can't take the risk of this happening again so I have switched to a different brand. Sorry Otter Box.

title: Love this shirt!
text: I love this shirt. It is even better than expected. It is a polyester and cotton blend, so it's nice and soft (not as starchy as a 100% cotton shirt) and won't shrink! And it is a nice loose fit, long enough (and the right cut) to wear with leggings, boots and a blazer, which is exactly what I wore to the Mumford show in Portland last night! The design isn't cheaply made of an iron on decal, so I don't think it's going to start to peel off after a few washes. High quality, I am very happy with this purchase. I am 5'6 and 150 lbs and ordered a medium, which was the perfect fit. A large would have been way too big (even if I was really busty the large would look like a nightgown), fyi.

title: Overall an A- case, so close to A+!
text: Overall I am very pleased with this case. I have dropped my phone several times on concrete floors, and it takes a pretty good beating at work. It hasn't gotten even the smallest scratch and the case absorbs the shock really well. It has two components, the grey soft case and then the white hard shell that fits over the gray part. It was very sturdy and doesn't slip off easily, and the soft gray part of the case has little "doors" that open over the ports for the charger and usb. The doors are the perfect size. The outer hard case is also easy to clean, I just use Windex and everything comes right off (not like rubber cases that get a greasy feel after a while). The screen protector meets the edge of the case so no harm can be done to the phone anywhere and dirt doesn't get stuck inside. As for cons, the buttons are hard to push and I have to use the hard edge of my finger nail to push them through the Otterbox case. No more powering on and off quickly or hurrying to turn your ringer volume down at work. Also this case is VERY difficult to remove. It's great because I know the case won't slip off my phone and leave it unprotected. But if you have to take out your battery and reset a glitchy phone it can be quite the project. On only my 2nd try of removing the case to get to the phone battery, the white shell cracked. I was being careful and had already broken 2 finger nails trying to remove it. The case still works just fine and clamps on to the inner soft case so it's not that big of a deal. But at one point I was actually afraid I would damage my phone trying to get the case off, and obviously the warranty won't cover me if that happens.

title: Best screen protectors I have ever used

The screen protectors also have perfect little cut outs for the "home" button at the bottom and camera/speaker functions at the top.

title: Fine for the price for still photography
text:
Overall: So this lens package for the price is decent if you are trying to do still photography, but you probably want to save your money if you are trying to shoot video.

The Good: The macro lens is legit and will get you super close up shots for details on still photography. The kaleidoscope lens was, surprisingly, the most useful of the bunch for some creative cinematography. The fish eye does do it's job, though not needed very often. The ND filter does work if you need to colorgrade your shot in camera a bit.
The Bad: the wide angle is no big dealâ€” only slightly wider than a normal phone camera shotâ€” I had ti take a video with it both on and off and then play it back to be able to see the difference: It's minute. The telephoto lens was primarily the reason I was buying this package, hoping to get a nice depth-of-field and rack focus effect on some video footage I was shooting. Unfortunately, the telephoto does not have a focus capability. The lens twists about a fraction of a mm and this results in the tiniest change in focus â€” though you will get a very shallow depth of field. Again, still photography this is fine. You cannot change focus from one subject to another on a different plane either in the background or foreground. In the end it is pretty much another macro lens that you can use from a few feet away, rather than being right on top of your subject. Unfortunately, trying to follow a moving subject while shooting video with a lens that close up that can't adjust it's focus is pretty much useless.
